===Verb===
{{en-verb}}
# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To [[open]] the [[mouth]] [[wide]]ly and take a long, rather deep [[breath]], often because one is [[tired]] or [[bored]], and sometimes accompanied by [[pandiculation]].
#: {{ux|en|I could see my students '''yawning''', so I knew the lesson was boring them.}}
#* {{RQ:Defoe Robinson Crusoe 2|url=http://name.umdl.umich.edu/004784951.0001.000|text={{...}} I found my self towards Evening, first empty and sickish at my Stomach, and nearer Night mightily enclin’d to '''yawning''' and sleepy {{...}}}}
#* {{circa|1773}} {{w|John Trumbull (poet)|John Trumbull}}, ''The Progress of Dulness'', Exeter, New Hampshire: Henry Ranlet, 1794, Part 1, p. 19,<sup>[https://books.google.ca/books?id=acNYAAAAcAAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false]</sup>
#*: And while above he spends his breath,
#*: The '''yawning''' audience nod beneath.
# To [[say]] while yawning.
#* '''1922''', {{w|Stephen McKenna (novelist)|Stephen McKenna}}, ''The Secret Victory'', New York: George H. Doran, Chapter Ten, p. 214,<sup>[https://archive.org/details/secretvictorymck00mckeiala]</sup>
#*: “I haven’t the least idea what I want to do,” he '''yawned'''.
#* '''1978''', {{w|Andrew Holleran}}, ''The {{w|Dancer from the Dance}}'', New York: Bantam, 1979, Chapter 8, p. 217,<sup>[https://archive.org/details/dancerfromdance00holl]</sup>
#*: “Oh,” Sutherland '''yawned''', “I’m too ''old'' for this.”
# To [[present]] a wide opening; [[gape]].
#: {{ux|en|The canyon '''yawns''' as it has done for millions of years, and we stand looking, dumbstruck.}}
#: {{ux|en|Death '''yawned''' before us, and I hit the brakes.}}
#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Hamlet|III|2|text=’Tis now the very witching time of night,<br>When churchyards '''yawn''', and hell itself breathes out<br>Contagion to this world.}}
#* {{RQ:Milton Paradise Lost|6|lines=874-875|url=http://name.umdl.umich.edu/A50919.0001.001|text={{...}} Hell at last<br>'''Yawning''' receavd them whole, and on them clos’d,}}
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} To open the mouth, or to [[gape]], through surprise or [[bewilderment]].
#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Othello|V|2|text={{...}} O heavy hour!<br>Methinks it should be now a huge eclipse<br>Of sun and moon, and that the affrighted globe<br>Should '''yawn''' at alteration.}}
#* '''1606''', {{w|Thomas Dekker}}, ''Nevves from hell brought by the Diuells carrier'', London: W. Ferebrand, <sup>[http://name.umdl.umich.edu/A20072.0001.001]</sup>
#*: {{...}} ''Hell'' being vnder euerie one of their Stages, the Players (if they had owed him a spight) might with a false Trappe doore haue slipt him downe, and there kept him, as a laughing stocke to al their '''yawning''' Spectators.
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} To be eager; to desire to swallow anything; to express desire by yawning.
#: {{ux|en|to '''yawn''' for fat livings}}
#* {{RQ:Landor Imaginary Conversations|I|Milton and Andrew Marvel|page=6|url=https://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/001024082|text=Fly not, as thou wert wont, to his embrace,<br>Lest, after one long '''yawning''' gaze, he swear<br>Thou art the best good fellow in the world,<br>But he had quite forgotten thee, by Jove!}}
